ng of musical expression begun in his earlier Music as Cultural Practice, he regards music not only as an object that invites aesthetic reception but also as an activity that vitally shapes the personal, social, and cultural identities of its listeners.In language accessible to nonspecialists but informative to specialists, Kramer provides an original account of the postmodernist ethos, explains its relationship to music, and explores that relationship in a series of case studies ranging from Haydn and Mendelssohn to Ives and Ravel.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMusicxPhilosophy and aesthetics. 0aPostmodernism. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Classical.2bisacsh  aart history.  acase study.  acharles ives.  aclassical music.  acultural politics.  acultural trope.  adaphnis and chloe.  adesire.  agender.  agoethe.  ahaydn.  aliterary theory.  amendelssohn.  amusic history.  amusic.  amusical expression.  amusical form.  amusical heritage.  amusical narratology.  amusicology.  aperformative.  apostmodern music.  apostmodernism.  apostmodernity.  arepresentation.  atutelage.  awestern art music.  awestern music.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052020700440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520918429?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520918429423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520918429/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles